🧾 1️⃣4️⃣ Final Interview Summary

Observer Pattern defines a one-to-many dependency where a change in one object automatically notifies all its dependent objects, enabling loose coupling and event-driven design.

🔑 1️⃣5️⃣ Memory Trick
Observer → “Notify everyone when something changes”

The problem: things that need to know when other things change
Imagine you're building a weather station app. You have a WeatherStation object that tracks temperature. Now you have three things that care about temperature changes — a PhoneDisplay that shows current temp, an EmailAlerter that sends an alert when it gets too hot, and a DataLogger that records every change to a file.
The naive approach wires them all together directly:
javaclass WeatherStation {
    private float temperature;

    void setTemperature(float temp) {
        this.temperature = temp;

        // Directly call everything that cares
        phoneDisplay.update(temp);
        emailAlerter.checkAndAlert(temp);
        dataLogger.log(temp);
    }
}
This works, but it's already fragile. The WeatherStation now knows about PhoneDisplay, EmailAlerter, and DataLogger. It imports them, holds references to them, and calls them by name. The moment your product manager says "add a SmartWatch display and a SlackNotifier", you crack open WeatherStation and add more lines — modifying a class that has nothing to do with displays or notifications. Its job is measuring weather, not managing a guest list of interested parties.
More insidiously: what if at runtime, a user disables email alerts? What if the DataLogger is only available in the paid tier? You'd need if statements scattered across setTemperature. The class becomes a mess of concerns that don't belong to it.
This is precisely the problem the Observer pattern solves.

The core idea: a subscription model
Think about how a YouTube channel works. A channel (the subject) doesn't know who its subscribers are individually — it just knows it has a list of them. When a new video is uploaded, it notifies all subscribers. Subscribers can join or leave that list at any time. The channel doesn't care who's watching — it just broadcasts, and whoever is subscribed receives it.
The Observer pattern is exactly this model applied to objects in code. The object whose state changes (called the Subject or Observable) maintains a list of interested parties (called Observers). When something changes, it loops through that list and notifies each one. It doesn't know what they do with that notification — that's entirely their business.
