The full code, piece by piece
java// ─── Step 1: The Observer interface ──────────────────────────────
// Every class that wants to be notified must implement this.
// The subject only ever talks to this interface — it never knows
// whether it's calling a PhoneDisplay or an EmailAlerter.
interface Observer {
    void update(float temperature);
}


// ─── Step 2: The Subject interface ───────────────────────────────
// Defines the subscription contract — how observers register
// and deregister themselves. Any class can become observable
// by implementing this.
interface Subject {
    void subscribe(Observer o);
    void unsubscribe(Observer o);
    void notifyObservers();
}


// ─── Step 3: The Concrete Subject ────────────────────────────────
class WeatherStation implements Subject {

    // The subscriber list — typed as the Observer interface,
    // so WeatherStation never knows the concrete types inside it.
    private List<Observer> observers = new ArrayList<>();
    private float temperature;

    // Any observer can add itself to the list at any time
    @Override
    public void subscribe(Observer o) {
        observers.add(o);
    }

    // Any observer can remove itself — crucial for avoiding
    // memory leaks and unwanted notifications
    @Override
    public void unsubscribe(Observer o) {
        observers.remove(o);
    }

    // Loop through the list and call update() on each observer.
    // WeatherStation does NOT know what they do with the data.
    @Override
    public void notifyObservers() {
        for (Observer o : observers) {
            o.update(temperature);  // pure delegation
        }
    }

    // When temperature changes, update the state and notify everyone.
    // This is the only place WeatherStation needs to "know" anything —
    // and all it knows is "call notifyObservers()".
    public void setTemperature(float temp) {
        System.out.println("\nWeatherStation: temperature changed to " + temp + "°C");
        this.temperature = temp;
        notifyObservers();
    }
}


// ─── Step 4: Concrete Observers ──────────────────────────────────
// Each observer is completely independent. Changing one has
// zero effect on any other, or on WeatherStation itself.

class PhoneDisplay implements Observer {
    @Override
    public void update(float temperature) {
        System.out.println("PhoneDisplay: showing " + temperature + "°C on screen");
    }
}

class EmailAlerter implements Observer {
    private static final float THRESHOLD = 35.0f;

    @Override
    public void update(float temperature) {
        // Each observer can react to the same data in its own way
        if (temperature > THRESHOLD) {
            System.out.println("EmailAlerter: ALERT! Sending heat warning email — "
                + temperature + "°C exceeds threshold");
        } else {
            System.out.println("EmailAlerter: temperature normal, no email needed");
        }
    }
}

class DataLogger implements Observer {
    @Override
    public void update(float temperature) {
        System.out.println("DataLogger: writing " + temperature + "°C to log file");
    }
}


// ─── Step 5: Client code ─────────────────────────────────────────
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        WeatherStation station = new WeatherStation();

        // Observers register themselves — WeatherStation didn't
        // ask for them, they came to it
        PhoneDisplay  phone  = new PhoneDisplay();
        EmailAlerter  email  = new EmailAlerter();
        DataLogger    logger = new DataLogger();

        station.subscribe(phone);
        station.subscribe(email);
        station.subscribe(logger);

        // All three observers are notified
        station.setTemperature(28.0f);

        // Unsubscribe phone at runtime — user closed the app
        station.unsubscribe(phone);

        // Now only email and logger receive this notification
        station.setTemperature(37.5f);
    }
}
```

Running this produces:
```
WeatherStation: temperature changed to 28.0°C
PhoneDisplay:  showing 28.0°C on screen
EmailAlerter:  temperature normal, no email needed
DataLogger:    writing 28.0°C to log file

WeatherStation: temperature changed to 37.5°C
EmailAlerter:  ALERT! Sending heat warning email — 37.5°C exceeds threshold
DataLogger:    writing 37.5°C to log file
Notice that when the phone unsubscribes and the temperature hits 37.5°C, WeatherStation does exactly the same thing it always does — loop through observers and call update(). It has no idea the phone left. It didn't need to be told. The list simply got shorter.

The push model vs the pull model
What you've seen above is called the push model — the subject pushes the data directly to observers through the update(float temperature) call. The observers receive the data whether or not they specifically asked for it.
There's an alternative called the pull model, where the subject notifies observers that something changed, but doesn't say what. The observers then pull the data they care about themselves:
java// Pull model: update receives the whole subject, not just data
interface Observer {
    void update(Subject subject);  // receives the subject itself
}

// Observer pulls only what it needs
class PhoneDisplay implements Observer {
    @Override
    public void update(Subject subject) {
        WeatherStation station = (WeatherStation) subject;
        // I only care about temperature, so I pull just that
        System.out.println("PhoneDisplay: " + station.getTemperature() + "°C");
    }
}
The push model is simpler and usually preferred when all observers need the same data. The pull model is better when different observers care about very different pieces of the subject's state — it avoids sending observers data they don't need and reduces coupling between the subject's method signature and the observers.

Adding a new observer — OCP at work again
Adding a SlackNotifier to the system is purely additive:
java// New file. Zero existing files touched.
class SlackNotifier implements Observer {
    @Override
    public void update(float temperature) {
        System.out.println("SlackNotifier: posting temperature update to #weather channel");
    }
}

// One new line at the call site
station.subscribe(new SlackNotifier());
WeatherStation doesn't change. PhoneDisplay, EmailAlerter, and DataLogger don't change. The pattern makes extension trivially easy precisely because the subject knows nothing about its observers beyond the update() method.

Three things the Observer pattern gives you
The first is loose coupling between subject and observers — WeatherStation and PhoneDisplay never import each other, never hold typed references to each other, and can evolve completely independently. The second is dynamic subscription — observers can join and leave at runtime, which is something you simply cannot do if the subject holds hardcoded references. The third is single responsibility — WeatherStation does one thing (measure weather), and each observer does one thing (display, alert, or log). Neither leaks responsibility into the other.

Where you see this pattern in the real world
Once you understand Observer, you start seeing it everywhere. Java's EventListener in UI frameworks is a direct implementation. JavaScript's addEventListener is Observer under the hood — a button (subject) maintains a list of click handlers (observers) and calls them all when clicked. React's state system notifies components when state changes. Message queues like Kafka are an industrial-scale Observer pattern — producers publish events, and any number of consumers subscribe to them. Even database triggers follow this model: a change in one table (subject) notifies a procedure (observer) that something happened.
